Crossing development (Project) located in the City of Hercules in Contra Costa County. This chapter
discusses the Transportation Assessment purpose, analysis methods, criteria used to identify impacts, and
The study’s purpose is to (1) conduct site specific impact analysis at new and adjacent intersections, (2)
provide fair share allocation percentages for mitigation measures of significant impacts identified in prior
transportation analyses under the California Environmental Quality Act (CEQA), and (3) evaluate the
proposed Project’s access, circulation, and parking. The Project site is located in the City of Hercules and is
bounded by Sycamore Avenue to the north, San Pablo Avenue to the south, the intersection of these two
streets to the east, and Tsushima Street to the west. Figure 1 shows the Project site vicinity. The
approximately 12 acre site is currently vacant with Ohlone Creek running north-south dividing the site
into an east and west side. The proposed Project is composed of a Safeway anchor supermarket on the
east side and retail land use, including an 18-pump fuel center, on the west side as shown on Figure 2
(see Chapter 3 Project Characteristics for further details)

southern border of the site. Local access is provided from Sycamore Avenue and Tsushima Street. Five

The operations of roadway facilities are described with the term “level of service” (LOS). LOS is a
qualitative description of traffic flow from a vehicle driver’s perspective based on factors such as speed,
travel time, delay, and freedom to maneuver. Six levels of service are defined ranging from LOS A (free
flow operating conditions) to LOS F (congested operating conditions). LOS E corresponds to operations
“at capacity.” When volumes exceed capacity, stop-and-go conditions result and operations are
designated LOS F. In Hercules, the maximum level of acceptable delay is associated with LOS D (around
55 seconds of delay) with the exception of intersections along San Pablo Avenue, where the City has
adopted LOS E (around 80 seconds of delay) as the maximum.

page.text: Traffic conditions at signalized intersections were evaluated using methodologies proposed by the
Transportation Research Board (TRB), as documented in the 2010 Highway Capacity Manual (2010 HCM)
. The HCM 2010 methods calculates control delay at an intersection based on inputs such as
traffic volumes, lane geometry, signal phasing and timing, pedestrian crossing times, and peak hour
factors. Control delay is defined as the delay directly associated with the traffic control device (i.e., a stop
sign or a traffic signal) and specifically includes initial deceleration delay, queue move-up time, stopped
delay, and final acceleration delay. These delay estimates are considered meaningful indicators of driver
discomfort and frustration, fuel consumption, and lost travel time. The relationship between LOS and
control delay is summarized in Table 1.

The Contra Costa Transportation Authority (CCTA) adopted the use of the 2010 Highway Capacity Manual method in
March 2013, the available software platform to evaluate intersection operations consistent with HCM 2010 methods
has been found to contain numerous computational “bugs.” As the HCM method for analyzing vehicle operations has
not changed between the 2000 and 2010 HCM, Synchro 7.0 was used in this study to calculate vehicle level of service.
For unsignalized (all-way stop controlled and side-street stop controlled) intersections, the 2010 HCM
method for unsignalized intersections was used. With this method, operations are defined by the average
control delay per vehicle (measured in seconds). The control delay incorporates delay associated with
deceleration, acceleration, stopping, and moving up in queue. Table 2 summarizes the relationship
between LOS and delay for unsignalized intersections. At side-street stop controlled intersections, the
delay is calculated for each stop-controlled movement, the left turn movement from the major street, as
well as the intersection average. The intersection average delay and highest movement/approach delay
are reported for side-street stop controlled intersections.

The Project would have a significant impact on the environment if it would cause an increase in traffic
which is substantial in relation to the traffic load and capacity of the street system (i.e., result in a
substantial increase in either the number of vehicle trips, or delay and congestion at intersections), or
change the condition of an existing street (e.g., street closures, changing direction of travel) in a manner
that would substantially impact access or traffic load and capacity of the street system. Significance
criteria are used to determine whether a Project impact is considered significant and therefore requires
mitigation. The City of Hercules strives to maintain LOS D operations at signalized intersections, with the
exception of San Pablo Avenue where LOS E is the threshold.
The Contra Costa Transportation Authority (CCTA) serves as the Congestion Management Agency (CMA)
for Contra Costa County. CCTA adopted the County’s first Congestion Management Program (CMP) in
October 1991. The most recent CMP is referred to as the 2011 CMP. The 2011 CMP requires an analysis
of any project that is expected to generate more than 100 peak hour vehicle trips. Within the CMP there
are Action Plans for specific regions that identify multi-modal traffic service objectives (MTSOs) for specific
freeways and roadway segments. The West County Action Plan for Routes of Regional Significance---
Update 2009 includes the City of Hercules
. The plan groups roadways into two categories: “Routes of
Regional Significance” (RORS) and “Basic Routes.” Discretionary projects that impact Routes of Regional
Significance by generating greater than 100 trips shall comply with the requirements of the adopted
Action Plans. Freeway segments and roadways in the project study area designated as RORS include SR-4
(John Muir Parkway), Interstate 80, and San Pablo Avenue. However, because the Project does not add
more than 100 new trips beyond what was previously addressed in 2009 EIR, it does not meet the 100
peak period threshold for addressing traffic impacts to the CCTA designated RORS.
The following thresholds will be considered in the evaluation of the Project from a transportation
Would the operations of a study intersection (except those along San Pablo Avenue) decline from
LOS D or better to LOS E or F, based on the HCM LOS method, with the addition of Project traffic?
Would the operations of a study intersection along San Pablo Avenue decline from LOS E or
better to LOS F, based on the HCM LOS method, with the addition of Project traffic?
Would the operations of an unsignalized study intersection decline from an acceptable level to an
unacceptable level with the addition of Project traffic, and would the installation of a traffic signal
at an unsignalized intersection, based on the Manual on Uniform Traffic Control Devices (MUTCD)
Peak Hour Signal Warrant (Warrant 3), be warranted?
Would the Project increase traffic volumes on a street beyond the expected capacity limits and
would the increase in traffic be noticeable to existing residents?
Would the Project result in a change in traffic patterns, including either an increase in traffic levels
or a change in location that results in substantial safety risks?
A revised West County Action Plan for Routes of Regional Significance is in process. Formal adoption will likely be
take place in early 2015. The Draft Action Plan has been incorporated into the Countywide Transportation Plan, which
is out for public review now.
Would the Project substantially increase traffic hazards to motor vehicles, bicycles, or pedestrians
due to a design feature (e.g., sharp curves or dangerous intersections) that does not comply with
Caltrans design standards or incompatible uses (e.g., farm equipment)?
Would construction traffic from the Project have a significant, though temporary, impact on the
environment, or would Project construction substantially affect traffic flow and circulation,
Would the Project fundamentally conflict with adopted policies, plans, or programs supporting
alternative transportation (e.g., bus turnouts, bicycle routes)?
Would the Project generate parking demands that are inconsistent with adopted municipal code
requirements or otherwise cause parking deficiencies that impact uses outside the Project area?

This chapter describes transportation facilities in the Project study area, including the surrounding
roadway network, transit, pedestrian, and bicycle facilities in the Project site vicinity. Existing intersection
Regional access to the Project site is provided by Interstate 80 (I-80). I-80 freeway connects the San
Francisco Bay Area with the Sacramento region and continues east. Near the Project site, I-80 is oriented
in a northeast/southwest direction about provides four lanes in each direction. Access between I-80 and
the Project site is provided via the I-80/State Route 4 interchange at Willow Avenue. The relocation of this
interchange farther east is proposed by the year 2035. I-80 is designated as a Route of Regional
Significance. The posted speed limit is 65 miles per hour.
State Route 4 (SR 4)/John Muir Parkway also provides regional access to the Project site. SR 4 has an
east/west orientation from the eastern border of the City of Hercules to its termination just west of San
Pablo Avenue within City limits. The facility is a four-lane freeway (two lanes in each direction) with a
partial-stack interchange at I-80 and a posted speed limit of 65 miles per hour. West of San Pablo
Avenue, the facility is a four-lane surface street with a posted speed limit of 35 miles per hour. SR 4 is
designated as a Route of Regional Significance.
San Pablo Avenue extends in a northeast/southwest direction through the City of Hercules and provides
regional and local access to the Project site. It begins in the City of Rodeo within Contra Costa County
and continues through the City of Hercules terminating in the City of Oakland in Alameda County. In the
study area, San Pablo Avenue provides two lanes in each direction with additional turning movement
capacity at intersections. Bicycle lanes are provided through the study area. Sidewalks are provided on
the south side of the street from SR 4/John Muir Parkway to Hercules Avenue; however, no sidewalks are
provided on the north side of the street between SR 4/John Muir Parkway and Tsushima Street (along the
Project frontage). No on-street parking is permitted on San Pablo Avenue and the posted speed limit
through the City of Hercules is 40 miles per hour. The posted speed limit to the west when approaching
the City of Pinole is 25 miles per hour. San Pablo Avenue is designated as a Route of Regional
Sycamore Avenue is an east-west roadway that provides access to the Project site as well as the
residential communities north of the Project site and residential communities out to the west along
Sycamore Avenue. It also provides access to retail and residential land use on the east side of I-80. From
Refugio Valley Road through San Pablo Avenue to South Front Street, Sycamore Avenue provides two
travel lanes in each direction with additional turning movement capacity at intersections and a posted
speed limit of 35 miles per hour. From South Front Street through Tsushima Street until its western
terminus, Sycamore Avenue provides one travel lane in each direction with no additional turning
movement capacity at intersections and a posted speed limit of 25 miles per hour. Bicycle lanes are
provided from Refugio Valley Road to the east and from San Pablo Avenue to South Front Street.
Sidewalks are provided on both sides of Sycamore Avenue throughout the study area. On-street parking
is prohibited east of South Front Street and permitted to the west. Angled parking stalls are provided
between South Front Street and Tsushima Street, and parallel spots are provided west of Tsushima Street.
Tsushima Street is a north-south roadway that connects San Pablo Avenue to John Muir Parkway and
borders the west side of the Project site. At present, left-turn access to and from the unsignalized
intersection of Tsushima Street and San Pablo Avenue is restricted by soft-hit posts in the striped median
of San Pablo Avenue. One travel lane is provided in each direction with no additional turning movement
capacity at intersections. No bicycle lanes are provided. Sidewalks are provided on both sides of the
street north of Sycamore Avenue, but only on the west side to the south. No sidewalks are provided
between San Pablo Avenue and Sycamore Avenue on the east side of the street (along the Project
frontage). The posted speed limit is 25 miles per hour.
Willow Avenue is primarily an east/west roadway within the City of Hercules. It extends from Sycamore
Avenue to the east, providing access to the I-80/SR 4 interchange ramps and to the Hercules Transit
Center. Between Sycamore Avenue and the Hercules Transit Center, generally one travel lane is provided
in each direction, with additional left turn movement capacity provided at intersections. The posted
speed limit is 35 miles per hour.
Pedestrian and bicycle volumes in the Project vicinity during the weekday AM and PM vehicle peak hours
are low, which is consistent with suburban/rural character of the area at present. Currently, the most
pedestrian activity is along the retail land use south of San Pablo Avenue. Figure 4 presents existing AM
and PM peak hour pedestrian and bicycle volumes at the study intersections.
As shown in Figure 5, pedestrian facilities in the study area include sidewalks, crosswalks, and pedestrian
signals. Local roadways in the study area provide sidewalks on both sides of the street with the exception
of the north side of San Pablo Avenue along the Project frontage and the east side of Tsushima Street
along the Project frontage. At both the Sycamore Avenue/Tsushima Street intersection and the Sycamore
Avenue/San Pablo Avenue intersection, crosswalks are provided across all legs of the intersections. At the
Sycamore Avenue/South Front Street intersection, crosswalks are provided across the north and west legs.
At the Tsushima Street/San Pablo Avenue intersection, no crosswalks are provided. Pedestrian countdown
signals are provided at the signalized intersection of San Pablo Avenue/Sycamore Avenue.
Bike paths (Class I) – Paved trails that are separated from roadways.
Bike lanes (Class II) – Lanes on roadways designated for use by bicycles through striping,
Bike routes (Class III) – Roadways designated for bicycle use by signs only; may or may not
include additional pavement width for cyclists.
San Pablo Avenue is a designated Class II facility with bike lanes spanning well past the Project area in

about 400 feet of Class II bike lanes on its south side, across from the Hercules Transit Center.

The Sycamore Crossing Project site is located in Hercules, California and is bounded by Sycamore Avenue
to the north, San Pablo Avenue to the south, the intersection of these two streets to the east, and
Tsushima Street to the west. The Project area compromises approximately 12 acres and is within 500 feet
of Interstate 80 (I-80). The site is currently vacant with a variable elevation and Ohlone Creek running
north-south dividing the parcel of land into an east and west side. The proposed Project consists of a
55,000 square feet Safeway anchor supermarket on the east side, 80,400 square feet of retail use
(including a fitness club, bank, pet supply store, fast casual dining restaurant and coffee shop with drive
thrus, sit-down restaurant, and specialty retail), and an 18 pump Safeway fuel center. The Project would
provide approximately 323 parking stalls on the west side of the creek and approximately 214 parking
stalls, including both surface parking and Safeway rooftop parking, on the east side of the creek. The site
Regional access to the site is provided from State Route 4 (SR 4) and Interstate 80 (I-80), with the
interchange just east of the site. Regional access is also provided via San Pablo Avenue serving as the
southern frontage of the site. Local access is provided from Sycamore Avenue and Tsushima Street. Five
new driveways are proposed into the site, three from San Pablo Avenue, one from Tsushima Street, and
one from Sycamore Avenue. Two driveways on San Pablo Avenue, one serving the fuel center and one
serving the supermarket, are right-in, right-out access only. The Tsushima Street driveway and Sycamore
Avenue driveway are full access driveways allowing both right and left turns, inbound and outbound. The
middle access point on San Pablo Avenue is the main entrance and is proposed to be signalized. The
Project also proposes to signalize the intersection of San Pablo Avenue/Tsushima Street and to modify the
intersection to provide a left-turn lane from San Pablo Avenue and allow full access (it is currently right-
turn-in/right-turn out with Stop sign control). Chapter 8 Site Plan Review provides further details on site
For clarification, Sycamore North, a mixed-use residential and retail project north of Sycamore Avenue
between Tsushima Street and South Front Street, is not connected with the Sycamore Crossing Project.
Trip generation refers to the process of estimating the amount of vehicular traffic a project would add to
the surrounding roadway system. Estimates are created on a daily basis and for the peak one-hour period
during the morning and evening commute periods when traffic volumes on the adjacent streets are
highest. For this study, several sources of information were reviewed in the development of trip
generation estimates, including trip generation rates from the Institute of Transportation Engineers (ITE)
Edition) and trip generation surveys conducted for similar land uses in
previous Fehr & Peers studies. ITE, which is considered the definitive source on trip generation, advises
that trip generation estimates should be taken from the counts of uses that are most comparable to uses
ITE Trip Generation includes trip generation rates for a variety of land uses based on actual land uses
located in typically suburban contexts throughout the United States. The corresponding ITE Trip
Generation Handbook includes rates for internal trips (i.e., the share of trips generated that remain within
the Project site such as a patron going to both the supermarket and the fuel center) and pass-by trips (i.e.,
trips already on the adjacent roadway where the driver decides to stop at the site such as a patron
purchasing an item on their way home from work) for various land uses. Internal trip reductions are also
based on the widely used National Cooperative Highway Research Program’s (NCHRP) Report 684,
Enhancing Internal Trip Capture Estimation for Mixed-Use Developments dated 2011 and NCHRP’s 8-51
Internalization tool, which is more current than the ITE Trip Generation Handbook.
Trip generation data previously collected by Fehr & Peers for Safeway supermarket and coffee shop land
uses resulted in lower rates than ITE. Conservatively, 9

except the fuel center (more information on the fuel center assumptions is presented below) to estimate
daily and peak hour vehicle trip generation. Table 4 shows the trip generating potential of the proposed
Project and Appendix A presents the specific rates and ITE land use codes used in calculations.
Approximately seven percent of trips are expected to be internal trips on a daily basis and during the
morning peak hour, and 15 percent in the evening peak hour. Five percent of trips would be
walk/bike/transit trips applied to all land use except the fuel center. Pass-by trips make up 40 percent of
trips to the supermarket, bank, specialty retail, coffee shop, restaurant, and fast-food; however, trips to the
fitness club and pet supply store were assumed to have no pass-by trip reduction as those are more
“intended destinations.” A 50 percent pass-by reduction is expected for the fuel center.

Safeway fuel centers have atypical (higher) trip generation characteristics when compared to a typical

Existing With Project conditions were evaluated using the same methods described in Chapter 1. The
Existing With Project analysis results are presented in Table 6, based on the vehicle volumes presented on
Figure 10. Table 6 also includes the operations results for Existing conditions for reference purposes. The
addition of Project traffic would increase average delay at the study intersections slightly, but would not

Intersection control at San Pablo Avenue/Tsushima Avenue (Intersection #1) and at San Pablo Avenue/
Shopping Center West Driveway/Main Entrance (Intersection #6) changes from Existing conditions to
Existing With Project conditions. The Project proposes to signalize both intersections. With the Project,
signal spacing will be average 500 feet between Tsushima Street and Sycamore Avenue, which will be
consistent with signal spacing in other urbanized areas such as Pinole 0.6 miles southwest on San Pablo
Avenue. Like that segment of San Pablo Avenue, it is likely that the change in character will justify a
reduction in the speed limit on San Pablo Avenue when engineering speed surveys are conducted after
At San Pablo Avenue/Shopping Center East Driveway/RIRO Supermarket Driveway (Intersection #5) delay
at the side-street improves significantly from LOS E to LOS B because northbound left turns under existing
conditions are shifted to the proposed signalized Intersection #6. Shifting these northbound left turns to
signalized Intersection #6 means vehicles departing the retail center and traveling westbound on San
Pablo will no longer wait for a gap in traffic to merge creating a safer driving experience. In addition, a
westbound left turn movement is added at Intersection #6 which provides additional signalized access
into the neighboring retail center with the Project.
Under Existing With Project conditions, the signal warrant met under Existing conditions at Intersection #5
is negated due to the Project’s shift in northbound left-turning vehicles from the neighboring retail center.
None of the unsignalized intersections meet signal warrants in either the morning or evening peak hours
under Existing With Project conditions. Signal warrant worksheets are provided in Appendix D.

intersection became the numerator in our analysis. The denominator was the cumulative vehicle traffic
growth from the 2009 EIR’s Cumulative Plus Project scenario (Cumulative 2035 Buildout Volume –
Existing No Project Volume). The percentages, presented in Table 9, represent the Project’s fair share
allocation to the mitigation improvements identified in the 2009 EIR.

page.text: This chapter presents a description of the proposed San Pablo street design, evaluates site access and
circulation for all modes of travel, reviews fuel center circulation and parking requirements, and analyzes
sight distance for the Supermarket driveway/San Pablo Avenue intersection. The site plan this review is
based on is presented on Figure 2.
In the study area, San Pablo Avenue is a four-lane facility, with two lanes in each direction. Currently,
adjacent to the Project site, it carries about 1,800 vehicles per hour (in both directions combined) during
both the AM and PM peak hours. About 60-65% of these (or 1,100 vehicles) travel in the peak commute
direction which is westbound in the morning and eastbound in the evening. The remaining 35-40% (or
700 vehicles) travel in the off-peak direction. For comparison, counts from the 2009 EIR (reflecting 2008
conditions) at the same location show that San Pablo Avenue carried about 2,200 vehicles per hour (in
both directions combined) during the AM peak hour and about 1,800 vehicles per hour during the PM
Under Cumulative 2035 conditions, San Pablo Avenue is projected to carry approximately 2,800 vehicles
per hour (in both directions combined) during both the AM and PM peak hours, exceeding the existing
counts by about 1,000 vehicles. While volumes have reduced between 2009 and 2014, two lanes in each
direction are necessary to meet the City’s level of service objectives for San Pablo Avenue. In addition,
San Pablo Avenue plays a regional role as a reliever route for I-80.
Based on the Sycamore Crossing Initial Planned Development Plan (2010), San Pablo Avenue within the
study area is projected to become a more urban environment. The current speed limit is 40 miles per
hour and this design speed is expected to decrease with the addition of urban land use, sidewalks,
pedestrian scale design elements such as street lighting, signals, crosswalks, and the removal of
acceleration and deceleration lanes. The roadway is envisioned to have a design speed of 25-35 miles per
hour with two 12-foot travel lanes in each direction, 6-foot bike lanes on both sides, and a 10-foot
landscaped median when turn lanes are not provided. The Central Hercules Plan envisioned on-street
parking on San Pablo Avenue, but none is proposed as part of this application. Provision of on-street
parking would require a greater dedication of property from this development and would reduce on-site
parking. The portion of San Pablo Avenue about 0.6 miles southwest in Pinole is a good corollary to what
is likely to occur adjacent to the Project site, with design elements that reinforce slower speeds and alert
drivers to the presence of pedestrians.
